that we've not signed
any new business in 10 weeks,

42
00:03:33,252 --> 00:03:35,620
so I hope you'll understand

43
00:03:35,688 --> 00:03:39,958
that this is a title only... For now.

44
00:03:40,025 --> 00:03:42,994
Well, it's almost an honor.

45
00:03:49,435 --> 00:03:52,403
What made you suddenly write that?

46
00:03:56,809 --> 00:04:00,445
Well, most of it was
in the letter, hopefully.

47
00:04:01,981 --> 00:04:05,817
But I think in my heart it was an impulse,

48
00:04:05,885 --> 00:04:08,353
because I knew what I needed
to do to move forward.

49
00:04:08,420 --> 00:04:11,589
Well, it was a gesture
we hope will be useful.

50
00:04:11,657 --> 00:04:14,659
We believe, obviously, that
lung cancer is avoidable

51
00:04:14,727 --> 00:04:17,529
and can be thwarted
with the right campaign.

52
00:04:17,596 --> 00:04:21,566
- But how?
- We know frightening medical facts are useless.

53
00:04:21,634 --> 00:04:25,103
- Half of us are smokers.
- I'm a smoker too.

54
00:04:25,171 --> 00:04:28,606
And you can forget about us.
I've worked $10 million campaigns

55
00:04:28,674 --> 00:04:30,508
that can't even get
people to change brands.

56
00:04:30,576 --> 00:04:32,310
I can tell you from the inside

57
00:04:32,378 --> 00:04:35,046
that the business is really
only about getting new smokers.

58
00:04:35,114 --> 00:04:36,948
Teenagers are a tough sell.

59
00:04:37,016 --> 00:04:39,517
Not to tobacco companies.

60
00:04:39,585 --> 00:04:41,386
They play on a two-pronged attack,

61
00:04:41,453 --> 00:04:43,621
promising adulthood and rebellion.

62
00:04:43,689 --> 00:04:47,492
But teenagers are sentimental as well.

63
00:04:47,560 --> 00:04:49,327
Have you heard their music?

64
00:04:51,864 --> 00:04:54,165
I can tell you a little
of what I have in mind.

65
00:04:54,233 --> 00:04:56,868
I have to say it's very interesting.

66
00:04:56,936 --> 00:04:58,670
Go on.

67
00:05:02,675 --> 00:05:05,243
What I'm suggesting
is a series of commercials

68
00:05:05,311 --> 00:05:06,978
that run during "Bandstand" and the like.

69
00:05:07,046 --> 00:05:10,448
Show mothers and daughters
or fathers and sons

70
00:05:10,516 --> 00:05:13,585
and that cigarettes are between them.

71
00:05:13,652 --> 00:05:17,422
And you show with a walk on the beach,

72
00:05:17,489 --> 00:05:19,857
baking cookies, playing catch,

73
00:05:19,925 --> 00:05:22,860
that the parents are
not long for this world.

74
00:05:22,928 --> 00:05:24,562
But they hate their parents.

75
00:05:24,630 --> 00:05:26,731
They won't be thinking about their parents.

76
00:05:26,799 --> 00:05:28,366
They'll be thinking about themselves.

77
00:05:28,434 --> 00:05:30,301
That's what they do.

78
00:05:31,870 --> 00:05:33,371
The truth is

79
00:05:34,807 --> 00:05:36,541
they're mourning for their childhood

80
00:05:36,609 --> 00:05:39,844
more than they're
anticipating their future,

81
00:05:39,912 --> 00:05:42,080
because they don't know it yet
but they don't want to die.

82
00:05:45,651 --> 00:05:48,620
If it helps, I can guarantee you
that Lucky Strike will hate this.

83
00:05:55,361 --> 00:05:57,428
- How'd it go?
- So did you get Cancer?

84
00:05:59,298 --> 00:06:01,032
Megan, can you get Mr. Cosgrove?

85
00:06:02,534 --> 00:06:04,235
We've got a meeting for another meeting.

86
00:06:04,303 --> 00:06:05,937
They were eating out of his hand.

87
00:06:09,875 --> 00:06:11,509
And even better, the board was loaded

88
00:06:11,577 --> 00:06:13,778
with fat cats just like you said.

89
00:06:13,846 --> 00:06:16,781
Don had a particularly empathic exchange

90
00:06:16,849 --> 00:06:18,383
with the C.E.O. of Dow chemical.

91
00:06:18,450 --> 00:06:20,618
Saran wrap would be nice.

92
00:06:20,686 --> 00:06:22,553
I'll take him out on the
links, let him beat me.

93
00:06:22,621 --> 00:06:25,156
Roger, this is a
philanthropic organization.

94
00:06:25,224 --> 00:06:26,958
Don and I think it best if
we approach from the rear.

95
00:06:28,927 --> 00:06:31,529
- Are we celebrating?
- Don got us to the top three.

96
00:06:31,597 --> 00:06:33,765
- Stupendous.
- Ken, sit down.

97
00:06:41,073 --> 00:06:44,075
Everett Marlowe at Dow is
a very charming fellow.

98
00:06:45,944 --> 00:06:48,846
Your father-in-law to be
is at corning, right?

99
00:06:48,914 --> 00:06:50,281
Well, they must be quite acquainted.

100
00:06:51,550 --> 00:06:53,184
I think that's likely.

101
00:06:53,252 --> 00:06:55,019
Well, I was thinking

102
00:06:55,087 --> 00:06:57,121
wouldn't it be fun to have
a foursome this weekend

103
00:06:57,189 --> 00:06:59,657
that includes your father-in-law,
yourself and Mr. Marlowe?

104
00:06:59,725 --> 00:07:01,626
Doesn't that sound like fun?

105
00:07:05,864 --> 00:07:08,166
I don't know.

106
00:07:08,233 --> 00:07:10,401
Ken, there's no reason to be suddenly shy.

107
00:07:10,469 --> 00:07:12,970
I'm sure if you impressed
Everett this morning

108
00:07:13,038 --> 00:07:15,173
that should be enough
to get him on the phone.

109
00:07:15,240 --> 00:07:16,974
Well, I just looked him in
the eye and convinced him

110
00:07:17,042 --> 00:07:19,444
I was some kind of idealistic businessman.

111
00:07:19,511 --> 00:07:21,312
How is it gonna look if
I call for a meeting?

112
00:07:21,380 --> 00:07:23,448
Pretty bad, I guess.

113
00:07:24,616 --> 00:07:27,352
But I'm not Pete.

114
00:07:27,419 --> 00:07:30,488
- Sorry about that.
- No, you're obviously not.

115
00:07:31,857 --> 00:07:34,025
Tom Vogel is our biggest client

116
00:07:34,093 --> 00:07:36,394
unless we sign Dow, which would be yours.

117
00:07:36,462 --> 00:07:38,863
Look, I love Cynthia's dad

118
00:07:38,931 --> 00:07:41,332
and I know that every account I
have will eventually leave me.

119
00:07:41,400 --> 00:07:42,867
That's awfully pessimistic.

120
00:07:42,935 --> 00:07:44,635
Well, it's not worth the risk.

121
00:07:44,703 --> 00:07:47,338
Cynthia's my life... My actual life.

122
00:07:49,708 --> 00:07:52,076
Fine, if you want to tuck it
between your legs, I'll call him,

123
00:07:52,144 --> 00:07:53,978
but I have to warn you,
I'm going to drop your name.

124
00:07:55,447 --> 00:07:57,181
You do whatever you want.

125
00:07:57,249 --> 00:07:59,984
Now if you don't mind,
I'm going to go service

126
00:08:00,052 --> 00:08:02,854
the 30% of this firm that are my clients.

127
00:08:12,531 --> 00:08:14,532
Hello, Carla. Is Sally home?

128
00:08:15,834 --> 00:08:18,136
She is, but you shouldn't be here.

129
00:08:18,203 --> 00:08:19,837
Are they moving today?

130
00:08:19,905 --> 00:08:23,307
Monday. That's the Salvation Army.

131
00:08:23,375 --> 00:08:26,110
Mrs. Draper's car is gone.
I just wanted to say hi.

132
00:08:26,178 --> 00:08:27,912
I don't know.

133
00:08:27,980 --> 00:08:30,114
Fine. I just want to say bye.

134
00:08:31,850 --> 00:08:34,285
She's upstairs.

135
00:08:34,353 --> 00:08:36,754
Don't be long. Mrs. Francis
just ran to the store.

136
00:08:36,822 --> 00:08:39,023
Thank you.

137
00:08:40,926 --> 00:08:42,627
It's Glen. Are you decent?

138
00:08:42,694 --> 00:08:44,429
Come in.

139
00:08:48,734 --> 00:08:50,568
You really shouldn't be here.

140
00:08:51,837 --> 00:08:54,605
So you're finally moving.

141
00:08:54,673 --> 00:08:58,142
This weekend while we're
in California with my dad.

142
00:08:58,210 --> 00:09:00,711
Jeez, is that where you're moving?

143
00:09:00,779 --> 00:09:02,213
No, we're moving to Rye.

144
00:09:05,584 --> 00:09:07,552
I'll be able to drive in a few years.

145
00:09:07,619 --> 00:09:09,821
- I can come visit.
- Really?

146
00:09:09,888 --> 00:09:11,522
Absolutely.

147
00:09:13,992 --> 00:09:16,060
I can send you postcards.

148
00:09:16,128 --> 00:09:17,929
I have your address.

149
00:09:17,996 --> 00:09:20,264
It's not that big a deal.

150
00:09:20,332 --> 00:09:22,400
I say goodbye to people all the time.

151
00:09:31,243 --> 00:09:33,811
Okay. Are you going to Disneyland?

152
00:09:33,879 --> 00:09:36,614
- Yes.
- Get me something.

153
00:09:48,360 --> 00:09:50,828
- What are you doing here?
- I'm sorry.

154
00:09:50,896 --> 00:09:53,097
- It's my fault.
- Get out.

155
00:09:54,666 --> 00:09:57,034
- What are you waiting for?
- Why do you hate me?

156
00:09:57,102 --> 00:09:58,870
You don't think I know what you're doing?

157
00:09:58,937 --> 00:10:01,873
- You could be friends with anyone!
- Just 'cause you're sad

158
00:10:01,940 --> 00:10:03,040
doesn't mean everybody has to be.

159
00:10:06,678 --> 00:10:08,579
I'm sorry.

160
00:10:08,647 --> 00:10:11,249
I didn't see the harm.
He wanted to say goodbye.

161
00:10:11,316 --> 00:10:14,685
- Did you leave them alone?
- They're friends, that's all.

162
00:10:14,753 --> 00:10:16,654
When did you decide that you're her mother?

163
00:10:17,890 --> 00:10:19,657
It was a mistake.

164
00:10:19,725 --> 00:10:21,692
There's no need for that kind of talk.

165
00:10:23,262 --> 00:10:24,762
You know what, Carla?

166
00:10:26,031 --> 00:10:27,632
I've been thinking

167
00:10:27,699 --> 00:10:29,667
and the distance is...

168
00:10:29,735 --> 00:10:31,836
I need someone new nearby,

169
00:10:31,904 --> 00:10:34,138
someone closer to the new house.

170
00:10:34,206 --> 00:10:36,274
This should square us for the week.

171
00:10:37,876 --> 00:10:40,545
Do you think I enjoy doing this?

172
00:10:40,612 --> 00:10:43,481
After all these years?
I won't have it, Carla.

173
00:10:46,919 --> 00:10:48,886
Well, someone has to
look after those children.

174
00:10:48,954 --> 00:10:51,656
Really? And where are your kids?

175
00:10:51,723 --> 00:10:54,592
- Are they all doctors and lawyers?
- You'd best stop talking now.

176
00:10:54,660 --> 00:10:58,863
- Where are you going?
- I'm going to say goodbye to the children.

177
00:10:58,931 --> 00:11:00,665
Do you think that's a good idea right now?

178
00:11:00,732 --> 00:11:02,567
It'll just upset them more.

179
00:11:02,634 --> 00:11:04,502
Some other time.

180
00:11:12,144 --> 00:11:14,412
The bungalow in San Pedro

181
00:11:14,479 --> 00:11:16,480
netted you 10 grand in profit.

182
00:11:16,548 --> 00:11:18,482
What's happening with the other house?

183
00:11:18,550 --> 00:11:21,886
I have a listing appointment with the
realtor when I get back from California,

184
00:11:21,954 --> 00:11:23,888
- but I have no idea what it's worth.
- It's ossining,

185
00:11:23,956 --> 00:11:25,590
but I say you'll more
than double your money,

186
00:11:25,657 --> 00:11:28,159
which is not bad for 10 years.

187
00:11:28,226 --> 00:11:30,528
What about the loss for what
I put into the company?

188
00:11:30,596 --> 00:11:32,563
That's an investment. It's not a loss.

189
00:11:32,631 --> 00:11:34,298
Don't be impatient.

190
00:11:34,366 --> 00:11:37,368
Enjoy the harvest. Plant some seeds.

191
00:11:37,436 --> 00:11:39,637
Maybe get a place of your own.

192
00:11:39,705 --> 00:11:42,740
Don't you want to go home someday
and see a steak on the table?

193
00:11:44,876 --> 00:11:47,311
So, Mary Sunshine,

194
00:11:47,379 --> 00:11:49,580
what's the capital gains? 48%?

195
00:11:49,648 --> 00:11:52,183
Mrs. Francis is on the phone.

196
00:11:52,250 --> 00:11:53,851
- It's urgent.
- You want me to go?

197
00:11:53,919 --> 00:11:55,486
It's always urgent.

198
00:11:57,122 --> 00:11:58,990
- Hello?
- I'm very sorry,

199
00:11:59,057 --> 00:12:00,691
and I know this will disrupt your plans,

200
00:12:00,759 --> 00:12:02,360
but I'm afraid I had to let Carla go today.

201
00:12:02,427 --> 00:12:04,328
What? What happened?

202
00:12:04,396 --> 00:12:06,731
Don, I have the children 99% of the time.

203
00:12:06,798 --> 00:12:08,265
This is a decision that I get to make.

204
00:12:08,333 --> 00:12:10,334
Well, can't I just hire
her back for the trip?

205
00:12:10,402 --> 00:12:13,337
No. I don't want her poisoning the well.

206
00:12:13,405 --> 00:12:15,272
I told the kids she's sick.

207
00:12:15,340 --> 00:12:17,441
So what the hell do I do,
Betty, with no help?

208
00:12:17,509 --> 00:12:21,145
I have meetings, two flights,
diapers, for Christ's sake.

209
00:12:21,213 --> 00:12:24,248
Then don't take them! They're used to it.

210
00:12:24,316 --> 00:12:26,117
We're going.

211
00:12:41,333 --> 00:12:44,201
Hey, pumpernickel,
there's nobody out front.

212
00:12:44,269 --> 00:12:46,270
- I already ate.
- Me too,

213
00:12:46,338 --> 00:12:48,439
and I ran into someone
I'd like you to meet.

214
00:12:48,507 --> 00:12:50,908
This is Carolyn Jones, like Morticia;

215
00:12:50,976 --> 00:12:53,544
Peggy Olson, advertising wunderkind.

216
00:12:53,612 --> 00:12:55,813
- Pleased to meet you.
- Do you mind?

217
00:12:58,016 --> 00:12:59,450
Carolyn was at a photo shoot

218
00:12:59,518 --> 00:13:01,752
modeling pantyhose of all things.

219
00:13:01,820 --> 00:13:04,388
She got fired and she has to make rent.

220
00:13:04,456 --> 00:13:08,259
Joyce witnessed my nervous breakdown
at Howard Johnson's today.

221
00:13:10,629 --> 00:13:12,329
Well hello, ladies.

222
00:13:12,397 --> 00:13:14,965
Peggy, I needed to talk to
you about my ABC meeting,

223
00:13:15,033 --> 00:13:16,567
but if I'm interrupting...

224
00:13:16,635 --> 00:13:19,036
Who is this lovely young thing?

225
00:13:19,104 --> 00:13:21,572
Harry, this is my friend Joyce.
I thought you'd already met.

226
00:13:21,640 --> 00:13:24,442
Harold Crane, head of media.

227
00:13:24,509 --> 00:13:27,044
- Carolyn Jones.
- No kidding.

228
00:13:27,112 --> 00:13:29,246
She's looking for work.

229
00:13:29,314 --> 00:13:31,115
That's hard to believe.

230
00:13:33,151 --> 00:13:35,586
As an actress, model?
What is your experience like?

231
00:13:35,654 --> 00:13:39,023
Well, I've been modeling,
at least until this morning.

232
00:13:39,091 --> 00:13:42,126
The Topaz people went nuts,
fired the people who hired me

233
00:13:42,194 --> 00:13:44,061
- and then me.
- But you didn't do anything wrong, did you?

234
00:13:44,129 --> 00:13:45,863
No, she didn't.

235
00:13:45,931 --> 00:13:47,531
Peggy, do you think you can help?

236
00:13:47,599 --> 00:13:49,200
Maybe.

237
00:13:49,267 --> 00:13:51,669
I'm sorry. You said Topaz fired everyone?

238
00:13:51,737 --> 00:13:54,638
- They were very brusque.
- People lose their heads.

239
00:13:54,706 --> 00:13:56,974
I'm sure it was a mistake, dear.

240
00:13:57,042 --> 00:13:58,943
We should be going, honey.

241
00:13:59,010 --> 00:14:01,212
Yes. Yes, of course.

242
00:14:01,279 --> 00:14:03,114
Pleased to meet you.

243
00:14:03,181 --> 00:14:04,982
We'll see what we can do, Carolyn Jones.

244
00:14:20,461 --> 00:14:23,063
Any luck?

245
00:14:23,130 --> 00:14:24,931
The hotel has a service,

246
00:14:24,999 --> 00:14:27,067
but the girls who can take
care of Sally and Bobby

247
00:14:27,134 --> 00:14:28,768
won't watch a two-year-old and vice versa.

248
00:14:28,836 --> 00:14:31,204
So I've arranged for two girls

249
00:14:31,272 --> 00:14:32,906
to cover the two mornings you're working.

250
00:14:32,973 --> 00:14:35,041
I thought you might need
someone for Disneyland

251
00:14:35,109 --> 00:14:38,178
and maybe handle the
Dodger game on your own.

252
00:14:38,245 --> 00:14:41,181
- Does that sound like a vacation?
- Maybe it'll be an adventure.

